          "body": "The inventory of 38:24-31 is the ancient Near Eastern equivalent of a published auditor's report. Every gram of gold, silver, and bronze donated by Israel is accounted for and assigned to a specific structural use. The gold totals 29 talents and 730 shekels — all used for the sanctuary's inner furnishings (ch. 37). The silver totals 100 talents and 1,775 shekels — sourced from the exact half-shekel ransom payment of each of the 603,550 numbered men (38:26; cf. Exodus 30:12-16). The hundred talents became the hundred foundation sockets of the sanctuary and the veil (38:27) — one talent per socket, the ransom price of each Israelite cohort literally cast into the building's foundation. The bronze totals 70 talents and 2,400 shekels, applied to all the outer-court structural bases and hardware (38:30-31). The arithmetic is transparent and verifiable. No fund is unassigned; no surplus is hidden. Peter Davids and Howard Hendricks both emphasize that financial integrity in the work of God is not an administrative afterthought — it is a test of whether the workers truly believe the gifts belong to God, not to them."
