        "excerpt": "Moreover, he made the laver of bronze with its base of bronze, from the mirrors of the serving women who served at the doorway of the tent of meeting.",
        "body": "Verse 8 is a single verse, yet it is the chapter's most theologically textured moment. The laver stands between the altar (where sin is atoned) and the tent entrance (where priestly service begins) — spatially and symbolically the midpoint of the journey from guilt to nearness. No priest could enter the holy place without first washing at the laver; failure to do so meant death (Exodus 30:20-21). The laver is not optional equipment; it is a structural requirement of the approach to God.\n\nWhat makes this verse singular is the material source: the bronze mirrors of the serving women. Polished bronze mirrors were precious, personal items — a woman's instrument of self-examination and presentation. These women, identified by their service (*tsava* — military service vocabulary) at the tent entrance, donated the instruments of self-regard to construct the instrument of priestly purification. The Targum Onkelos and several early Jewish interpreters read these women as devoted servants who had relinquished vanity for service, and the narrative seems to honor them: the laver is the only furnishing in the entire tabernacle whose material source is identified by the identity of its donors.\n\nThe theological move is deliberate. What is used to examine the self is surrendered so that the self can be made clean for God's presence. The laver made from mirrors becomes an emblem of the whole sacrificial logic: what belongs to us, offered to God, is transformed into a means of His holiness. John Owen in his commentary on Hebrews notes the parallel: the priestly purification at the laver anticipates the believer's cleansing by the washing of water with the word (Ephesians 5:26; Titus 3:5), the sanctification by the Spirit that fits us for approach to the Father.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kiyyor* (laver) — a large basin for washing; the same word used for the large basins in Solomon's temple (1 Kings 7:38). *Tsava* (served) — the root of the armies of Israel and the heavenly hosts; these women were organized, dedicated corps. *Marah* (mirrors) — polished bronze reflective surfaces; the word's echo in *mar* (bitter) is probably not in view here, but the contrast between self-reflection and divine service is structurally embedded in the verse."
