        "body": "The courtyard section (38:9-20) reads as a perimeter survey: south, north, west, east, gate. Each side is measured in cubits, its number of posts and sockets recorded, its materials specified. The repetition can feel numbing, but the narrator is doing theology through arithmetic. The court is **complete**: all four sides, all posts, all sockets, all hooks and bands, the gate screen. Nothing is approximate; nothing is omitted. The comprehensiveness is the point.\n\nThe material hierarchy encodes holiness spatially. The foundations of the courtyard posts are bronze (38:17) — the same metal as the altar in the outer court, the metal of judgment and endurance. The hooks, bands, and caps of the posts are silver (38:17) — the ransom metal, the metal of redemption. Moving inward from the courtyard toward the tent, the observer would see gold replacing silver and silver replacing bronze. You can read the theology from the outside in: bronze (judgment), silver (redemption), gold (glory). The court's architecture is a catechism in the structure of salvation.\n\nThe gate screen (38:18-19) is the exception to the plain linen perimeter. Embroidered in blue, purple, and scarlet on fine twisted linen — the same four-color combination as the inner veil (Exodus 26:31) and the high priest's ephod (Exodus 28:6) — the gate announces that this is not an ordinary threshold. The entrance is marked by beauty that the surrounding walls do not share. In ancient Near Eastern sacred architecture, the gateway was always the most ornate element because it was the point of transition between the common and the sacred. Israel's gate points east — toward the sunrise — and the worshiper walks westward, toward the divine presence, against the direction of the world.\n\nThe single gate matters as a canonical image. Psalm 118:20 — 'this is the gate of the LORD; the righteous will enter through it' — uses the same spatial logic. There is one way in. Jesus' identification of Himself as the door (John 10:9) and the way (John 14:6) draws on exactly this architectural theology. The tabernacle's one eastern gate, embroidered in the colors of holiness and royalty, is a prefiguration of the exclusive mediation of Christ.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chatser* (courtyard) — the same word used for a walled enclosure around a house; the tabernacle is God's household, and the court is its perimeter. *Masakh* (screen/curtain, 38:18) — the hanging barrier; the same root governs the inner veil (*porekhet*), linking the gate screen to the curtain before the holy of holies: both are thresholds requiring authorization to cross."
